# Controller-Contract Preamble — Template (v1)

There are exactly two valid shapes for a R.Code command file. Pick ONE.

## 1. Substantial commands (the default)

Any command that decomposes work and dispatches mutating sub-work (most
`/issue`-style, `/brainstorm`-style, `/rcode-*` commands) uses the full
contract. Paste this block verbatim, right after the closing `---` of the
YAML frontmatter. The linter does not match on marker syntax alone — it also
requires three specific prose lines inside the body (see "What the linter
checks" below). The block below is the real shape used by `commands/meta.md`
and `commands/team-lead.md`, both of which pass the linter today; adapt only
the surrounding instructional prose to the command's actual flow, not the
three bolded lines themselves.

```
<!-- controller-contract:v1 -->
> **Controller-First.** This is a substantial R.Code entry point: decompose the work via the controller before mutating anything (see `agents/control-agent.md` §1-2).
> **Model×Effort per spawn** is assigned via `agents/control-agent.md` §2 — the single canonical dispatch spec; do not re-derive it here.
> **Second-order checkpoints** run after every delegation wave per `agents/control-agent.md` §4.
```

Why these exact three lines: the linter greps for `Controller-First`,
`Effort per spawn.*agents/control-agent\.md.*§2`, and
`Second-order checkpoints` (checks #3 below) — reword the surrounding prose
freely, but keep those three substrings intact and in the order shown, on
lines that still contain their required neighbors (the "Effort per spawn"
line must still mention `agents/control-agent.md` and `§2` on the SAME
line).

There is no separate `2ND-ORDER-CHECKPOINT` marker pair — the third bolded
line above is what the linter checks; a distinct closing/opening marker for
the same fact does not exist in any command on disk and is not required.

## 2. Read-only / mechanical commands (exempt)

Commands that only read state and never dispatch mutating work (e.g.
`handoff`, `simple-onboard`, `status-sync`) declare exemption via an inline
`exempt="<reason>"` attribute on the SAME `controller-contract:v1` marker —
there is no separate exemption marker. This is the real shape used by
`commands/handoff.md`, `commands/simple-onboard.md`, and
`commands/status-sync.md`, all of which pass the linter today:

```
<!-- controller-contract:v1 exempt="read-only/mechanical, no agent dispatch" -->
```

Replace the reason text with a real one-line justification specific to the
command. The linter extracts and stores the reason (it does not validate its
content), but a real reason is what makes the exemption reviewable by a
human later. When the marker carries `exempt="..."`, checks #1, #2, and #3
below are skipped entirely for that command — checks #4 and #5 still run.

## Frontmatter requirements (both shapes)

Every command file needs YAML frontmatter with, at minimum:

```yaml
---
description: <one line>
model: claude-fable-5[1m]   # substrate pin — IMP-092 landed; every command
                             # on disk today is pinned to claude-fable-5[1m]
                             # (agents/control-agent.md is pinned to the same
                             # value). Other values remain syntactically
                             # legal per command-contract-lint.sh's
                             # allowed-substrate pattern (short aliases
                             # opus/sonnet/haiku/fable, or full
                             # claude-<family>-<n>[1m] ids) — override via
                             # CLAUDE_CONTRACT_MODEL_RE if a command
                             # genuinely needs a different substrate — but
                             # claude-fable-5[1m] is the default to copy.
allowed-tools:               # for the SUBSTANTIAL shape, must include one of:
  - Task                     #   Task, TaskCreate, or TaskUpdate
  - Read
  - ...
---
```

The exempt shape does not require `Task`/`TaskCreate`/`TaskUpdate` in
`allowed-tools` (check #2 is skipped when the marker carries
`exempt="..."`), but still needs `model:` if the command should run on a
specific substrate — it is simply not linter-enforced for exempt commands.

## What the linter checks (scripts/command-contract-lint.sh)

| # | Check | Exempt commands |
|---|-------|------------------|
| M | `<!-- controller-contract:v1 -->` marker present (lowercase, HTML comment); its optional `exempt="<reason>"` attribute is the only exemption signal | still runs — the marker itself must be present either way |
| 1 | `model:` frontmatter present, value matches the allowed-substrate pattern | skipped |
| 2 | `allowed-tools` contains `Task`/`TaskCreate`/`TaskUpdate` | skipped |
| 3 | Body contains all three mandatory lines: `Controller-First`, `Effort per spawn.*agents/control-agent\.md.*§2`, `Second-order checkpoints` | skipped |
| 4 | No stale references (`autonomy-arbiter.md`, `excessive-agency-gate.md`, `ux-agent`, `frontend-agent`) — a line that historically explains a stale reference (contains `archiv`/`superseded`/`retired`/`ersetzt` on the same line) is exempted | still runs |
| 5 | Every `**<name>-agent**` mention resolves to a real `agents/<name>-agent.md` | still runs |

Run it: `bash scripts/command-contract-lint.sh commands/`

Note the linter takes a **directory** argument (defaults to
`~/.claude/commands` if omitted), not a single file — point it at the
directory containing the command file(s) you want checked.
